english:
  title: Three Poems on Songdo
  author: Lee Seung-so
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I.

    Deep gorges lock away the purple mist of Jahadong,
    But where stands the pavilion of the Minister's house?
    The fairy maiden departed once and left no word—
    Only empty music lingers, singing of wine and joy.

    II.

    Ogwan Mountain rises level with white clouds,
    Old trees thrust toward heaven while cuckoos call.
    A filial son's pure wind has blown through ages—
    Still travelers hum the song of little Tang.

    III.

    At Tohyeon, bright clouds unfold like white silk,
    At Pagyeon, cascading waters pour down silver streams.
    Raising my whip to gaze as the sun descends,
    I sweep the green moss and inscribe these brief verses.
  footnotes:
    - Jahadong (자하동) refers to a legendary grotto associated with ancient Korean mythology, symbolizing a sacred or hidden place.
    - The 'fairy maiden' and 'Minister's house' allude to historical or legendary figures connected to Songdo (松都), likely referencing Goryeo's capital Kaesong.
    - Ogwan Mountain (오관산), Tohyeon (토현), and Pagyeon (박연) are scenic locations associated with Songdo.
    - The reference to 'little Tang' (소당계) and the cuckoo's cry evoke traditional Korean poetic imagery of sorrow and remembrance.
    - This is a series of three poems (삼수) contemplating the ruins and natural beauty of the ancient capital.
